cs|1|cp|4|fp|1|HT|e|AT|^-{A Prologue}
^-|CP||fp||AT|^C@2^y@3This is a short journal outlining my struggle learning bridge and my attempt to join the elite players by learning the coveted 2 over 1, while hardly can declare a minimally complex auction. I would be happy if it helps you learn 2 over 1 with more ease and less confusion. However, please do not expect a Marco Polo journal. To learn 2 over 1 you can find great sources--several of them are listed later. 

Retired and feeling useless, two years ago I decided to learn bridge. My wife purchased beginner books after talking with Mr. Marty Bergen and I added couple bridge CDs. I foolishly thought there was nothing to it. I figured in six to maximum eight weeks I would Ace it and beat everyone in our local club.

Six and even eight weeks went by and I was more a source of humor in our club than a champion. Undaunted, I decided to expand my reach and increase the time spent on conquering the beast. So, I had great experience with Fifth Chair and Richard Pavlicek web sites and finally and thankfully landed in BBO and BIL, where Maureen took me under her wings and my real hard work began. 

In BBO/BIL, I was like a child in a candy shop. I met many great teachers who were teaching for free and had time to answer questions. I also met many players who were  brave and willing to play with me and help me go forward without stepping on too many cow pies

You may say I was in bridge heaven and decided to learn the best system there was. Yes, I was really a newbie and thought I should learn the most advanced system that ws available, until a wise teacher who later became my mentor and shaped my bridge structure told me, "First, learn SAYC well then you can go on to other advanced areas."  Later, I will share with you an inventory of what I have learned in SAYC which I can still use while playing 2 over 1. |
