cs|1|cp|4|fp|1|HT|E|at|^-{A Prologue}
^-|CP||FP||AT|^C@2^y@3Two years later when I finally decided to take the plunge my mentor response to my e-mail query was,

^*b"1) Most expert players prefer 2 over 1. Up until a few years ago, 2 over 1 was really "advanced SAYC" (e.g. inverted minors, limit or Bergen Raises, RKCB, negative doubles, and so forth) plus the 2 over 1 stuff. However, now SAYC includes many advanced conventions. Therefore, although I would still say 2 over 1 is somewhat of an improvement over SAYC, the difference is not nearly as great, so if you just stuck to SAYC, on most hands, you would not be at a disadvantage. I still think it is a good idea for you to learn 2 Over 1, but it will not improve your bidding as much as you might otherwise think, because you know a lot of advanced conventions already.

2) Almost all SAYC conventions are used in 2 over 1. There are really only two differences, in major suit auctions. If you bid 2 over 1 of a major, that is a game force. And, if you respond 1N to one of a major, that is a one round force. And those differences only apply if there is no interference. Other than those two differences, SAYC and 2 Over 1 Auctions are identical.

3) Basically, you need some criteria to decide if you have a game forcing hand. I play that having a rule of 20 hand qualifies as a game forcing hand, and is the easiest and best way for you to make that decision."^*N

Well that sums it up. Seriously, now I know all there is to 2 over 1. But, I have another point to tell you. While I am at it I really want to build a scaffolding for my "how to open one of the majors and proper responses to such openings" while learning 2 over 1 and burn it on my forehead. Another good teacher told me, "In part, you already are playing 2 over 1. You have to close the circle."   |
