cs|1|cp|4|fp|1|HT|E|at|^-{               My New Tool Box - and 2 over 1               }
|CP|8|AT|Openings while playing 2 over 1
^-|CP||FP||AT|^C@2^y@3Adding 2 over 1 to the tool box should not be that difficult. Remembering all the nuances is the hard part. Let me check my original tool box and see what I have and whether I should discard a few old tools or add a few new ones. After all a heavy tool box does not necessarily make me a good mechanic. Now, let me examine the tools in the box one by one. BTW, I hope you recall that this is my learning process. So bear with me.

1. I will open one of major any |cp|8|at|"suitable"|cp||at| hand. By now, I should know the hand evaluation, HCPs, the quality of the suits, the quick tricks, the defensive tricks, Rule 20 and most importantly the new hand evaluation by Marty Bergen.

2. At any chance, except at fourth seat, I will pre-empt 2D, 2H, and 2S holding a |cp|8|at|"suitable"|cp||at| hand. Howard teaches, "I think any time you have 5-10 points and a six card suit (assuming you don't meet the rule of 20), you should open a weak two." I  would be a bit more cautious on the "suitable" part though. No disrespect Howard, I am not that good of declarer as yet.

3. Open 2C with the proper hand and/or point count. 

4. Yes, with "real" 20-21 HCPs and a balanced hand I love to open 2NT. I even do it with five card major. I may even do it with two doubleton. However, I like at least one of those doubletons fully stopped.

5. For minors, however, I love the line by Mike Lawrence and he says,|cp|8|at|

"Rule: With balanced hands on which you decide not to bid a major suit, bid the longer of your minor suit. If minor suits are three cards only, open one club."|cp||at|

|
PG| ***** 4 ***** |


NT||

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%Page 2
cs|1|cp|4|fp|1|HT|e|at|^-{               My New Tool Box - and 2 over 1               }
|CP|8|AT|Openings while playing 2 over 1
^-|CP||fp||at|^C@2^y@3Further, I almost always open one diamond if I have 4-4 in minors unless the Diamonds are really puny. Of course I know that only with 4-4-3-2 shape we open one diamond.

6. As I said, I open 1H/1S any suitable hand with 5 card plus in that major. With 5-5 I open the higher ranking. With  five spades and five clubs I can flip a coin. But, I do not know about you because I always fumble the ball when I get a great hand with 5 Spades and 5 Clubs or 5/6 and etc. So, again let me share with you what Howard suggests and I will follow.

"With 5/5, you always open the higher ranking suit (skip spades and clubs for a minute), ^*Bnot the stronger suit^*N. This is to make your bidding more economical, as you can repeat your 2nd suit at a lower level, and partner can correct to the higher ranking suit at the same level. Even with reverse level strength, you open your higher ranking suit. If you reverse, your first suit is always longer than your second suit."

"Now with spades and clubs there are two theories. In the old days, you opened 1C, because you then got to repeat your spades at the 2 level, allowing partner to correct to 3C. If you opened spades, and then bid clubs twice, partner would have to correct 3C to 3S, so you would be higher. However, these days, most people open 1S with 5/5 in the blacks, the idea being that, particularly with all the preempting that is going around, you want to get your spade length across as early as possible. So, take your pick and make sure partner agrees. If playing with an unfamiliar partner, open 1S." 

"With 6/5, if you have less than a reverse, you open the higher ranking suit, even if it is the 5 card suit. With reverse strength, if your lower ranking suit is a six card suit, you can open in the lower ranking suit and reverse into the higher ranking suit (because your opening suit is still longer than your second suit)."
|
