cs|1|cp|4|fp|1|HT|E|at|^-{               My New Tool Box - and 2 over 1               }
|CP|8|AT|Openings while playing 2 over 1
^-|CP||fp||at|^C@2^y@37. My favorite is 1NT opening. Strictly, balanced hands and 15-17 point and no more than one doubleton. Five card major is no problem.  And, I also like the following by Mike Lawrence, |cp|8|at|"If your hand contains the correct number of points to open one notrump, do it except when it is clearly right to open something else."|cp||at| Needless, to mention that in another book he backtracks a bit on 5-card majors. There, he suggests opening one of major if the suit is very strong. I like to keep my bidding simple so I open 1NT with any 5-card major. I had concerns regarding including Qx and Jx in my 15-17 points. But, Marty Bergen solved that problem for me. He has a simple and fairly reliable method to determine an accurate value of your hand before any bidding. He calls that value "Starting Points" which is a God's gift for me. No more memorizing "so many ways to love my hand." 


8. Okay, let us forget the openings with esoteric hands (such as six or seven of this or that) which I may see once in a blue moon.

So far, I am relived that all my hard learned SAYC rules are compatible with 2 over 1 and I can go to the next step. But, after all said and done I like to keep the following self made rule:|Cs|4|at|^-

{CAREFULLY, CONSIDER MY REBID BEFORE OPENING THE HAND}
^-|at|
That should keep me out of lot of troubles.
