st||sk||rh||ah|OPENER'S REBID OPTIONS|ah|Quiz|ah|Board  1|sv|0|md|1skq73hq9863d7ckqj,,|mb|1hp2dp|lb|*BWhat bid would you make?^^2h|MB|2H|NT|
^b@2^b@2Bid ^*B2H^*N. Some experts play rebidding your suit shows a six card suit.  I (Mike Lawrence), and many others, strongly disagree.  All of the alternatives are terrible. 2NT with a singleton in partner's suit is bad.  He is entitled to assume you have at least two cards in his suit. 2S is a reverse.  Even though partner showed a good hand, a reverse still shows real values.  After a two over one from your partner, rebidding two of your suit is often the default bid when no other bid makes sense.  Your partner is not allowed to raise at this point without three card support so you are not at risk of your partner's hanging you.  |
