%%%%%%%%%%%%%b10
st||sk||rh||ah|OPENER'S REBID OPTIONS|ah|Quiz|ah|Board 10|sv|0|md|1skjthk8763daq83c2,,|mb|1hp2dp?|lb|*BWhat bid would you make?^^4c|mb|4c|NT|
^b@2Bid ^*B4C^*N.  You promise a stiff club and excellent diamond support.  I think you should have four card support, but will admit that three is OK if the rest of the hand is good.  One nice thing about a two over one response is that it usually shows a five card suit.  If your partner does not have one, he usually has support for your major. Singleton honors, even the ace, are worth less than you wish.  They do not rate to be as useful as high cards in the other suits.  If you have a singleton honor, make sure the rest of your hand is up to standards.  In other words, if you have a singleton honor and a minimum hand, it is best not to make the splinter bid.|
pg| ***** 240 ***** |


NT|
^B@2What you just read was from Mike Lawrence. However, since I like to  play the "control bids" then I like Howard's recommendation here, "although 4C is a splinter, I don't think it is a good bid, as you just bypassed 3N, which is the best contract more often than not. So, I would bid 3D. Granted, you might occasionally miss a slam when the singleton club is important, but if you play the control bids, you can usually describe the singleton later.|
PG| ***** 241 ***** |


