^-
The range for this bid is fifteen to seventeen since other ranges can be shown easily enough. So what kind of fifteen to seventeen would open with a major and then jump to 3NT?  One suggestion was to play it showed a singleton in partner's suit.  This is easy to reject since it means, among other things, that you have another suit that you might be better off bidding.  Another suggestion was to say it showed a six card major and a notrump type hand.  But, since you can rebid two of your major and then bid notrump, this was rejected.  The answer that seems best, after sifting through many opinions, came from my wife, Karen.  

Play that a 3NT rebid shows the fifteen to seventeen point hand with TWO LITTLE cards in partner's suit.  This makes sense because having two little cards is a fair reason not to open 1NT in the first place.  And it comes with a big extra benefit.  Your partner will often want to bid on after your 3NT bid and his knowledge that you have two small cards in his suit may give him enough information that he can choose wisely.|
